Today’s focus was on privilege escalation, standard permissions, and the sticky bit in Linux. These topics are essential for understanding system security and access control, especially in cybersecurity and system administration.

Key Takeaways:
Privilege Escalation: Learned how users can elevate their privileges in a Linux environment and its associated security risks.
Standard Permissions: Reviewed read, write, and execute permissions for users, groups, and others.
Sticky Bit: Explored how the sticky bit protects files in shared directories.
Hands-On Practice: Since I missed part of yesterday’s lesson, I worked independently to create user accounts using CLI commands to reinforce my learning.
Final Thoughts:
Understanding permissions and privilege escalation is crucial for security, and today’s session helped me see the importance of proper user access management. Working alone to complete the missed tasks was a great way to ensure I fully grasped the material. Excited to continue building on these skills!
